<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!DOCTYPE plist PUBLIC "-//Apple//DTD PLIST 1.0//EN" "http://www.apple.com/DTDs/PropertyList-1.0.dtd">
<plist version="1.0">
<dict>
  <!-- Required for WKWebView JIT compilation -->
  <key>com.apple.security.cs.allow-jit</key>
  <true/>
  <!-- Required for WebKit unsigned memory -->
  <key>com.apple.security.cs.allow-unsigned-executable-memory</key>
  <true/>
  <!-- Required for loading Tauri plugins as dylibs -->
  <key>com.apple.security.cs.disable-library-validation</key>
  <true/>
  <!--
    Apple Events automation (osascript → Finder, …).

    Added in v0.30.0 for the Finder-selection feature: Ctrl+Shift+F
    shells out to `osascript -e 'tell application "Finder" to get
    selection'` so the popup can list the files you have selected and
    run actions (resize, …) on them.

    With Hardened Runtime this entitlement is REQUIRED — without it
    AppleEvents are denied at the kernel level before the user even
    sees a TCC prompt. The companion piece is `NSAppleEventsUsageDescription`
    in Info.plist (injected by `scripts/install-macos.sh` post-build),
    which provides the human-readable copy macOS shows in the "App
    wants to control Finder" prompt.

    Historical note: a previous version of this comment warned against
    this entitlement on the grounds that it triggered an extraneous
    Automation prompt on macOS Tahoe when the app didn't actually need
    AppleEvents (just synthetic input via `CGEventPost`, which is
    gated by Accessibility — not by this entitlement). That concern
    no longer applies; we DO use AppleEvents now, and the prompt the
    user sees is the correct one for the feature.
  -->
  <key>com.apple.security.automation.apple-events</key>
  <true/>
  <!--
    Microphone access for the live BPM detector (v0.45.0+). The user
    types `bpm` in the popup and presses Enter; the overlay calls
    `navigator.mediaDevices.getUserMedia({ audio: true })` which
    under Hardened Runtime requires BOTH this entitlement AND the
    `NSMicrophoneUsageDescription` key in Info.plist (injected by
    `scripts/install-macos.sh` post-build), AND user consent via the
    TCC mic prompt that fires on first use.

    No system-audio capture here — just mic. macOS doesn't have a
    "system audio" device exposed via getUserMedia anyway; that
    would need ScreenCaptureKit + its own TCC grant.
  -->
  <key>com.apple.security.device.audio-input</key>
  <true/>
</dict>
</plist>
